"Ghafoori E., Flynn P.C., Checkel M.D.","Global warming impact of electricity generation from beef cattle manure: A life cycle assessment study",2006,"International Journal of Green Energy","3","3",,"257","270",,,10.1080/01971520600704423,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33748078125&partnerID=40&md5=c572d5b4e85cb1e8b320a094f5ae6bd8","Mechanical Engineering Department, University of Alberta, Edmonton, AB, Canada","Ghafoori, E., Mechanical Engineering Department, University of Alberta, Edmonton, AB, Canada; Flynn, P.C., Mechanical Engineering Department, University of Alberta, Edmonton, AB, Canada; Checkel, M.D., Mechanical Engineering Department, University of Alberta, Edmonton, AB, Canada","We compare calculated greenhouse gas emissions for a North American beef feedlot operation, which includes biogas production by anaerobic digestion with subsequent electricity generation (the AD case), to the emissions for a ""business as usual"" case, which includes both a feedlot and an equivalent amount of grid-generated electricity. Anaerobic digestion, biogas production and electricity production are the major sources of differences in emissions. Fertilizer production, crop production, manure collection and spreading, as well as the associated transport stages are also considered within the LCA system boundaries; impacts on life cycle emissions from these sources are lower. Running a feedlot and producing electricity using typical grid power plants produces 3,845 kg CO2.eq/MWh while running a feedlot, which generates biogas to produce electricity, produces 2,965 kg CO2.eq/MWh. This savings of 880 kg CO2.eq/MWh arises because the net power generation in the AD case emits about 90% less life cycle GHG emissions compared to grid-average electricity. The high overall emission levels arise due to emissions associated with enteric fermentation in beef cattle as the main source of GHG emissions in both the ""business as usual"" and the AD cases. It contributed 57% of total emissions for the feedlot /biogas /electricity system and 44% of total emissions for the feedlot /grid electricity system. Copyright © Taylor &amp; Francis Group, LLC.","Anaerobic digestion; Beef feedlot; Biogas utilization; Electricity generation; Greenhouse gas emission; Life cycle assessment","Anaerobic digestion; Biogas; Crops; Electric power generation; Fermentation; Fertilizers; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Manures; Beef feedlot; Biogas utilization; Electricity generation; Life cycle assessment; Life cycle; anoxic conditions; biogas; carbon dioxide; electricity generation; emission; environmental impact assessment; global warming; greenhouse gas; life cycle analysis; manure; power generation; power plant; Bos taurus",,,,,,"(2004) Agricultural Operation Practices Act (AOPA), , AAFRD (Alberta Agriculture, Food and Rural Development). [ISBN 0779730593]. Edmonton, AB, Canada: Alberta Queen's Printer; Custom rates survey; grain harvesting operations (2004) Statistics and Data Development Unit, , http://www1.agric.gov.ab.ca/&dollar;department/deptdocs.nsf/all/sdd4303, AAFRD (Alberta Agriculture, Food and Rural Development). Alberta, Canada; Manure production and characteristics [D384.1:] (2003), ASAE Standards. St. Joseph, Michigan: ASAEBasarab, J.A., Okine, E.K., Baron, V.S., Marx, T., Ramsey, P., Ziegler, K., Lyle, K., Methane emissions from enteric fermentation in Alberta's beef cattle population: A model methodology for Canada (2005) Canadian Journal of Animal Science, 85, pp. 501-512. , http://www.csa.com/htbin/linkabst.cgi?issn=8408-3984&vol=85&iss= &firstpage=501; Beauchemin, K.A., McGinn, S.M., Methane emissions from feedlot cattle fed barley or corn diets (2005) Journal of Animal Science, 83, pp. 653-661. , http://www4.infotrieve.com/newmedline/detail.asp?NameID= 15705762&Session=&searchQuery=Journal+of+ Animal+Science%5BJournal+ Name%5D+AND+83%5BVolume%5D+AND+653%5BPage+ Number%5D+AND+2005%5BPublication+Date%5D+AND+Beauchemi